      "`a n = (1 / n : ℝ)^{2025}`.\n2. Define `b : ℕ → ℝ` by `b n = (1 / n : ℝ)^2`.\n3. Show that for all `n ≥ 1`, `a n ≤ b n`.\n4. Show that `∑' n : ℕ, b n` is finite.\n5. Deduce that `∑' n : ℕ, a n` is finite by the comparison test (but Lean's `tsum_le_tsum` requires that `a` and `b` are nonnegative, which they are).\n\nBut in Lean, for `n = 0`, `a 0 = 0` and `b 0 = 0`. For `n ≥ 1`, `a n ≤ b n`.\n\nSo, we have `a n ≤ b n` for all `n`. Then:\n```\n∑' n : ℕ, a n ≤ ∑' n : ℕ, b n < ∞.\n```\n\nBut we must confirm that Lean knows `∑' n : ℕ, b n < ∞`.\n\nAlternatively, we can note that for `n ≥ 2`, `a n ≤ 1 / n²`, because `n^{2025} ≥ n²` (since `n ≥ 1` and `2025 ≥ 2`), and `(1 / n)^{2025} ≤ (1 / n)²`.\n\nBut perhaps it's better to use that `(1 / n)^{2025}` is bounded by a summable sequence (e.g., `1 / n²`). \n\n### Direct Proof in Lean:\n\nWe can use the fact that for all `n : ℕ`, `(1 / (n : ℝ))^2025 ≤ (1 / (n : ℝ))^2`, except perhaps for `n = 0`, but in Lean, `(1 / (0 : ℝ))^2025 = 0` and `(1 / (0 : ℝ))^2 = 0`, so the inequality is always true.\n\nBut perhaps more precisely:\n\nFor `n = 0`: `(1 / (0 : ℝ))^2025 = 0 ≤ 0 = (1 / (0 : ℝ))^2`.\n\nFor `n ≥ 1`: `(1 / (n : ℝ)) ∈ [0,1]`, so raising to a higher power makes it smaller: `(1 / (n : ℝ))^2025 ≤ (1 / (n : ℝ))^2`.\n\nSo, `(1 / (n : ℝ))^2025 ≤ (1 / (n : ℝ))^2` for all `n : ℕ`.\n\nNext, we need to show that",
      "series ∑ (1/n)^2 is summable to prove that it is also 2025-summable\n  have h₂ : Summable fun n : ℕ => ((1 : ℝ) / n : ℝ) ^ (2025 : ℝ) := by\n    have h₃ : Summable fun n : ℕ => ((1 : ℝ) / n : ℝ) ^ (2 : ℝ) := by\n      -- Prove that the series ∑ (1/n)^2 is summable\n      have h₄ : Summable fun n : ℕ => ((1 : ℝ) / n : ℝ) ^ (2 : ℝ) := by\n        -- Use the fact that the series ∑ (1/n)^2 is summable\n        have h₅ : Summable (fun n : ℕ => (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ) ^ 2) := by\n          -- Use the p-series test with p = 2 > 1\n          have h₆ : Summable (fun n : ℕ => (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ) ^ 2) := by\n            -- Use the fact that the series ∑ 1/n^2 is summable\n            simpa [pow_two] using\n              (summable_nat_add_iff 1).mpr (Real.summable_one_div_pow.mpr (by norm_num : (1 : ℕ) < 2))\n          exact h₆\n        -- Convert the summable series to the desired form\n        have h₇ : (fun n : ℕ => (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ) ^ 2) = (fun n : ℕ => ((1 : ℝ) / n : ℝ) ^ (2 : ℝ)) := by\n          ext n\n          cases n with\n          | zero =>\n            norm_num\n          | succ n =>\n            field_simp [pow_two]\n            <;> ring_nf\n            <;> norm_num\n            <;> field_simp [pow_two]\n            <;> ring_nf\n            <;> norm_num\n        rw [h₇] at h₅\n        exact h₅\n      exact h₄\n    -- Use the fact that (1/n)^2025 ≤ (1/n)^2 for n ≥ 1 to prove summability\n    have h₄ : (∀ n : ℕ, n ≥ 1 → ((1 : ℝ) / n : ℝ) ^ (2025 : ℝ) ≤ ((1 : ℝ) / n : ℝ) ^ (2 : ℝ)) := by\n      intro n hn\n      have h₅ : (n : ℝ) ≥ 1 := by exact_mod_cast hn\n      have h₆ : (0 : ℝ) < (1 : ℝ) / n := by positivity\n      have h₇ : (1 : ℝ) / n ≤ 1 := by\n        have h₈ : (n : ℝ) ≥ 1 := by exact_mod_cast hn\n        have h₉ : (1 : ℝ) / n ≤ 1 := by\n          rw [div_le_iff (by positivity)]\n          nlinarith\n        exact h₉\n      -- Use the fact that x^a ≤ x^b for 0 < x ≤ 1 and a ≥ b\n      have h₈ : ((1 : ℝ) / n : ℝ) ^ (2025 : ℝ) ≤ ((1 : ℝ) / n : ℝ) ^ (2 : ℝ) := by\n        -- Use the fact that the function x ↦ x^k is decreasing for 0 < x ≤ 1 and k ≥ 1\n        have h₉ : (2 : ℝ) ≤ (2025 : ℝ) := by norm_num\n        have h₁₀ : 0 < (1 : ℝ) / n := by positivity\n        have h₁₁ : (1 : ℝ) / n ≤ 1 := by\n          have h₁₂ : (n : ℝ) ≥ 1 := by exact_mod_cast hn\n          have h₁₃ : (1 : ℝ) / n ≤ 1 := by\n            rw [div_le_iff (by positivity)]\n            nlinarith\n          exact h₁₃\n        -- Use the fact that x^a ≤ x^b for 0 < x ≤ 1 and a ≥ b\n        exact Real.rpow_le_rpow_of_exponent_ge (by positivity) (by linarith) (by linarith)\n      exact h₈\n    -- Use the comparison test to prove summability\n    have h₅ : Summable fun n : ℕ => ((1 : ℝ) / n : ℝ) ^ (2025 : ℝ) := by\n      refine' Summable.of_nonneg_of_le (fun n => _) (fun n => _) h₃\n      · -- Prove that (1/n)^2025 ≥ 0\n        by_cases h₆ : n = 0\n        · -- If n = 0, then (1/n)^2025 = 0\n          subst h₆\n          norm_num\n        · -- If n ≠ 0, then (1/n)^2025 > 0\n          positivity\n      · -- Prove that (1/n)^2025 ≤ (1/n)^2 for n ≥ 1\n        by_cases h₆ : n = 0\n        · -- If n = 0, then (1/n)^2025 = 0 ≤ (1/n)^2 = 0\n          subst h₆\n          norm_num\n        · -- If n ≠ 0, then use the fact that (1/n)^2025 ≤ (1/n)^2 for n ≥ 1\n          have h₇ : n ≥ 1 := by\n            by_contra h₈\n            have h₉ : n = 0 := by\n              omega\n            contradiction\n          exact h₄ n h₇\n    exact h₅\n  -- Prove that the series ∑ (1/n)^2025 is summable\n  have h₃ : Summable fun n : ℕ => ‖((1 : ℝ) / n : ℝ)‖ ^ (2025 : ℝ) := by\n    have h₄ : (fun n : ℕ => ‖((1 : ℝ) / n : ℝ)‖ ^ (2025 : ℝ)) = (fun n : ℕ => ((1 : ℝ) / n : ℝ) ^ (2025 : ℝ)) := by\n      ext n\n      simp [Real.norm_eq_abs, abs_of_nonneg, div_nonneg, Nat.cast_nonneg, zero_le_one]\n      <;>\n      (try { cases n <;> simp [Nat.cast_add, Nat.cast_one, pow_add, pow_one, mul_comm] <;> norm_num }) <;>\n      (try { positivity }) <;>\n      (try { field_simp [Nat.cast_ne_zero] <;> ring_nf <;> norm_num })\n    rw [h₄]\n    exact h₂\n  -- Use the fact that the series ∑ (1/n)^2025 is summable to prove that GEO is in ℓ^2025\n  simpa [GEO, norm_eq_abs] using h₃",
